{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a53cac4-a6ac-4211-8236-01c23fbf1720","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page`.\n\n**Before (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**After (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n    <!-- your content -->\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n`SafeAreaRegions` is a flags enum — you can also target specific edges:\n\n```xml\nSafeAreaRegions=\"Top,Bottom\"\n```\n\nValid values: `None`, `All`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`.\n\nYou can also remove the `xmlns:ios` namespace import if it was only used for `UseSafeArea`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e95bf43d-2c3f-41c5-8ef8-236ccab37b12","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property was removed/deprecated. The new approach uses padding or the `SafeAreaRegions` property.\n\nLet me recall what I know:\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, the `UseSafeArea` platform-specific was replaced. The new approach is to use `Page.SafeAreaRegions` or set padding manually. Specifically, .NET 10 introduced a cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property that replaces the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea`.\n\n\nThe replacement uses a cross-platform property that accepts values like `All`, `None`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, and `Right` to control which safe area regions the page respects. I'm not entirely certain of the exact property name—it could be `SafeAreaRegions` or possibly `IgnoreSafeArea`—but the concept is that Microsoft unified safe area handling across platforms in .NET 10 rather than keeping it iOS-specific. The most likely replacement in .NET 10 is either a new cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property or continuing to use the platform-specific `On<iOS>().SetUseSafeArea(true)` approach, though MAUI's direction seems to be moving toward more consistent cross-platform safe area handling. Setting up the XAML property...","outputTokens":1602,"requestId":"980E:1E4705:1C8C76C:1F8B21E:6A05210B"},"id":"c9066f27-7698-4f8c-8557-d3ca20188e42","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:11:39.194Z","parentId":"2cae6d69-da04-4fea-b4fd-edaf8148cbce"}
